Code-specific vs general embedders — the semantic quality lever, proven
========================================================================

Question: does a CODE-TRAINED embedding model beat general text embedders for
code search? Earlier fused [lexical+semantic+graph] runs were inconclusive
because BM25 dominates any query that shares words with symbol names. To judge
the EMBEDDER alone, this test isolates the semantic arm: embed the query, cosine
over the stored vectors, NO BM25, NO graph. Queries are phrased with ZERO
lexical overlap with the target code, so BM25 could not have helped anyway.

Models compared (all via their /v1/embeddings endpoints; keys scrubbed):
  - all-minilm            (general, local, 384-dim)
  - nomic-embed-text      (general, local, 768-dim)
  - openai/text-embedding-3-small (general, cloud, 1536-dim)
  - mistralai/codestral-embed-2505 (CODE-trained, cloud, 1536-dim, 8K context)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
THE DISCRIMINATING QUERY (no word overlap with the steering code):
  "inject a new instruction to redirect the assistant mid-flight without
   restarting"   -> ground truth: steer / job_steer / agent.steer, agent_loop
--------------------------------------------------------------------

General models (fused view, all three): top hits were run_turn / run_agent_loop
/ Agent — NEVER the steering mechanism. They cannot map the concept to the
domain term "steer".

Codestral (code model), PURE SEMANTIC, chunk=512:
  0.617 append_thinking            (agent_loop.rs:445)   <- mid-run msg inject
  0.613 replace_last               (agent_loop.rs:456)
  0.604 append_delta_to_last       (agent_loop.rs:464)
  0.603 continue_                  (agent.rs:272)
  0.602 steer                      (agent.rs:235)        <- THE function
  0.598 steering_message_injected_mid_run (loop_test.rs:269)

Codestral, PURE SEMANTIC, chunk=4000 (fuller bodies, within its 8K window):
  0.660 steering_message_injected_mid_run   (loop_test.rs:269)
  0.646 on_steering_injects_message_mid_run (loop_hooks_test.rs:146)
  0.617 append_thinking                     (agent_loop.rs:445)
  0.613 replace_last                        (agent_loop.rs:456)
  0.610 steering_queue_primitive_injects_mid_run (loop_test.rs:283)
  0.604 append_delta_to_last                (agent_loop.rs:464)
  -> top 5 are ALL steering / mid-run injection. Fuller context ranks the
     steering tests even higher.

Second concept query "detect that a file was modified so its cached parse must
be rebuilt" (ground truth: refresh / reparse), Codestral pure semantic:
  chunk=512:   RefreshStats #1, reparse_check #2, read_cached, parse_file
  chunk=4000:  refresh (store.rs:108) #1  <- the ACTUAL function, top hit;
               RefreshStats #2, reparse_check #3

--------------------------------------------------------------------
END TO END (the product, not an offline script): fused code_search with the
Codestral index on the lexically-neutral steering query:
  1. steering_queue_primitive_injects_mid_run (loop_test.rs:283)
  2. steering_message_injected_mid_run         (loop_test.rs:269)
  3. assistant                                 (compaction.rs:255)
  4. steer                                     (agent.rs:235)  [10 callers]
  -> top 4 are steering. The hybrid surfaces the right code when BM25 isn't
     hijacking the query.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
VERDICT
--------------------------------------------------------------------
A code-specific embedder is the real semantic-quality lever — proven, not
assumed. General models (any size, local or cloud) miss domain-concept queries;
Codestral maps "inject an instruction mid-flight" -> `steer` effortlessly. The
earlier "all embedders look the same" reading was a BM25-domination artifact in
the fused view, exposed by isolating the semantic arm.

Fuller chunks help (512 -> 4000 pushed the real target function to #1).

Cost (OpenRouter): codestral-embed-2505 is $0.15 / 1M input tokens. A full
2137-symbol index of pirs (~270K tokens) costs ~$0.04, one time; queries embed
one short string (~10 tokens); re-index touches only changed files. Negligible.

Wiring: zero code changes — the OpenAI-compatible embed client + background
indexer already consume it:
  --semantic --embed-base-url https://openrouter.ai/api/v1 \
  --embed-model mistralai/codestral-embed-2505 --embed-api-key <key> \
  --embed-max-chars 4000
(Cloud embeddings mean code leaves the machine — a privacy/cost trade, fine for
a public repo, weigh it for private code.)
